R

  1. Create a single density estimate of a numerical column of your choice by using he density geom.

  2. Try setting the alpha parameter to a float between 0 and 1 and the fill parameter to a color name as a string to get a shaded density, which I find visually appealing =) Set these inside the geom, not inside the aes function.

  3. Do you think either of this density plot or the histogram in the previous exercise gives you a better understanding of the underlying data? Which one and why?

In[5]:
ggplot(movies, aes(x = runtime)) +
  geom_density() +
  labs(
    x = "Runtime (minutes)",
    y = "Density",
    title = "Density of movie runtime"
  )
In[7]:
ggplot(movies, aes(x = runtime)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4, fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(
    x = "Runtime (minutes)",
    y = "Density",
    title = "Density of movie runtime"
  )

Compared to the histogram in the previous exercise, I find the density plot more helpful for understanding the underlying distribution of runtime. The density curve smooths out the binning artifacts of the histogram and makes it easier to see the overall shape of the distribution (such as skewness and whether it is unimodal or multimodal). However, the histogram is better if we care about the actual counts in each range.

Question 1.3

rubric={viz:2,accuracy:2}

R

  • Pipe the data fame's numerical columns (except id) into ggplot (the .select_if() method can help here, or you can do it manually).
  • Copy the code from your density plot above and paste it here. Modify the code so that it accepts the piped dataframe and plots one density estimate per column in a plot grid with 2 columns and 3 rows. Dont use a loop, use pivoting and faceting instead (example in the lecture videos).
In[9]:
movies %>%
  select(where(is.numeric), -id) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "variable", values_to = "value") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4, fill = "steelblue") +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Density",
       title = "Density plots of numerical movie variables") +
  theme_minimal()

2. Pairwise numerical columns

Question 2.1

rubric={viz:1,accuracy:1}

R

Next, lets look at the relationships between pairs of numerical columns.For this we will create a scatterplot matrix (SPLOM) for all numerical columns except id.

There is nothing built into ggplot for this but the GGally package has a handy ggpairs function for this, which also plots single column densities on the diagonal and correlation coefficients on the upper corner. Install this package an then use the ggpairs.

In[13]:
library(GGally)
library(tidyverse)
movies %>%
  select(where(is.numeric), -id) %>%
  ggpairs()

Question 2.2 (Optional)

R

We're getting close, dont give up! Remember, we're in it for the $$$

  1. There is nothing built into ggplot for correlations but the GGally package has a handy ggcorr function we can use. You could also calculate it manually and use geom_tile if you prefer.

In[14]:
library(GGally)
library(tidyverse)

movies %>%
  select(where(is.numeric), -id) %>%
  ggcorr(label = TRUE, label_round = 2)

I prefer the GGally ggcorr plot for viewing correlations because it is compact and immediately shows both the sign and strength of relationships using a consistent color scale and numeric labels. Its quick to spot the strongest positive/negative pairs at a glance. The Altair version is nicer for interactivity (hover, filtering), but for a static report, ggcorr is clearer and easier to read.

R

Let's create a explosion in R. In the tidyverse, exploding a list / vector from a column is referred to as unnesting it, less action-packed but maybe even more descriptive? =)

I have already done the necessary wrangling here, but please view the df so that you understand what happened and check out tidyr doc for a simpler example.

  1. Use this new dataframe and create multiple violinplots inside a single figure by having genres on the y-axis and revenue on the x axis.
  2. Read the documentation of the violin plot to find out how you can use its parameters to add a line for the median (hint: the same as quantile 0.5).
  3. As we did in the previous lecture with add_count(), we need to create a new column for sorting, this time using mutate(). I want you to sort the genres by median revenue, so that the median lines of the violin plots are nicely sorted. I have given you a skeleton below where you can fill in the blanks, but you are also free to do it your own way. Then use the same function as previous lectures to sort by this new column.
In[31]:
library(tidyverse)
free_genres <- movies %>%
  unnest(genres)
In[32]:
free_genres <- free_genres %>%
  group_by(genres) %>%
  mutate(median_revenue = median(revenue, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()
In[33]:
free_genres <- free_genres %>%
  mutate(genres = fct_reorder(genres, median_revenue))
In[34]:
ggplot(free_genres, aes(x = revenue, y = genres)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.4) +
  stat_summary(
    fun = median,
    geom = "crossbar",
    width = 0.3,
    color = "black"
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  labs(
    x = "Revenue",
    y = "Genre",
    title = "Movie revenue distributions by genre (sorted by median)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Question 3.3 (Optional)

rubric={accuracy:0.5,reasoning:0.5}

R

  1. Copy over the code from the faceted violinplots above.
  2. In contrast to boxplots, violinplots can show an indication of counts by scaling their area based on the number of observations instead of keeping it the same in all violins. Read the violin plot documentation and find the variable that controls the scaling of the area and change it so that the violins indicate the count of the observations.
  3. Compare this to the approach we used in Altair for a boxplot + a barplot for counts, which approach do you think is clearer for getting a feeling for the number of observation in each group and why?
In[24]:
library(tidyverse)

free_genres <- movies %>%
  unnest(genres) %>%
  group_by(genres) %>%
  mutate(median_revenue = median(revenue, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(genres = fct_reorder(genres, median_revenue))

free_genres %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = where(is.numeric) & !median_revenue,
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "value"
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value, y = genres)) +
  geom_violin(scale = "count", fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.4) +  # <- 
  stat_summary(fun = median, geom = "crossbar", width = 0.3, color = "black") +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free_x") +
  labs(
    x = NULL,
    y = "Genre",
    title = "Violin plots (area scaled by count) of numerical variables by genre"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Compared to the Altair approach (boxplot + separate bar chart for counts), scaling violin widths by count is a quick, integrated way to hint at sample size. However, I find the boxplot + bar chart clearer for understanding counts because the bars provide an explicit, easily comparable scale. The count-scaled violins can be harder to read precisely, especially when many categories are close in size.

In[25]:
library(tidyverse)

free_studios <- movies %>%
  unnest(studios) %>%
  group_by(studios) %>%
  mutate(median_revenue = median(revenue, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(studios = fct_reorder(studios, median_revenue))

free_studios %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = where(is.numeric) & !median_revenue & !id,   #  id  median_revenue
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "value"
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value, y = studios)) +
  geom_boxplot(color = "darkorange", fill = "darkorange", alpha = 0.35, outlier.alpha = 0.25) +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free_x") +
  labs(
    x = NULL,
    y = "Studio",
    title = "Boxplots of numerical variables by studio (sorted by median revenue)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
In[26]:
free_studios %>%
  count(studios, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = studios)) +
  geom_col(fill = "darkorange", alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(
    x = "Count",
    y = "Studio",
    title = "Number of movies per studio"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Two patterns stand out. First, some studios have a high median revenue but relatively few movies, suggesting they focus on fewer blockbusters rather than volume; Id like to check whether this persists after adjusting for budget. Second, studios with many movies often show wide variability (long upper tails) in revenue and budget, raising the question of whether portfolio diversity or franchise strategy drives the spread. These are worth exploring with log scales and per-year trends.

4. EDA of categorical columns

Question 4.1

rubric={viz:1,accuracy:1}

  1. Go through the GGally example plots and find a plot that you think is suitable for showing the count of the combination of categorical variables. Use this plot to visualize the counts.
  2. Create another plot of the counts by first using add_count() to add a count for all the combinations of genres and studios. This column will be called n and you can map it to an appropriate aesthetics encoding and visualize the results with geom_tile to create a heatmap of counts.
In[29]:
library(tidyverse)
library(GGally)

cat_df <- movies %>%
  unnest(genres) %>%
  unnest(studios) %>%
  select(genres, studios)

GGally::ggpairs(cat_df)
In[28]:
movies %>%
  unnest(genres) %>%
  unnest(studios) %>%
  add_count(genres, studios, name = "n") %>%
  distinct(genres, studios, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = studios, y = genres, fill = n)) +
  geom_tile() +
  labs(
    x = "Studio",
    y = "Genre",
    fill = "Count",
    title = "Heatmap of counts for (genre, studio) combinations"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

rubric={accuracy:1}

R

The plots above are great for comparing absolute counts, but that means that studios with smaller production volume gets drowned out. Let's instead visualize the proportion within each studio for each genre. Calculate the proportion for each studio - genre pair, so that for each studio, the genre proportions adds up to 1. Visualize with your favorite categorical count plot.

movies %>%
  unnest(genres) %>%
  unnest(studios) %>%
